\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Important messages:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
An increase in advertising may lower the commodity price to household(by
 raising g), and thereby increase its demand for the commodity(Z) and change
 its demand for the firm's output(x).
 Consequently, advertising affects consumption in this formulation not by
 changing tastes, but by changing prices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Even a firm faced with a fixed commodity price(
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{x}$
\end_inset

) in a perfectly competitive commodity market can sell its product at different
 prices(
\begin_inset Formula $p_{x}$
\end_inset

) by varying the levels of advertising.
 Since an increase in advertising would increase the commodity output that
 consumers received for a given amount of firm's output, the price of the
 product(
\begin_inset Formula $p_{x}$
\end_inset

) would then increased relative to the fixed commodity price(
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{x}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A firm can have many perfect substitutes in the commodity market even if
 there are only a few firm that produce the same physical product.
 For instance, a firm may be a sole designer of jewelery that contribute
 to the social prestige(commodity) of consumer, but there are many products
 that contribute to social prestige such as fashionable clothes, race car,
 and etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The optimal advertising for a firm can be found by maximizing its income
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
I & = & p_{x}X-TC(X)-Ap_{a}\\
TC(X) & = & \text{Total cost of production}\\
p_{a} & = & \text{Cost of a unit advertising}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

